# Remove punctuation. 

def removePunc(text):
    import string as st
    t=[w for w in text if w not in st.punctuation]
    return ''.join(t)


def removeSymbols(x):
    t = re.sub(r"[^a-zA-Z0-9?!.,]+", ' ', x)
    return t


df['tweet'] = df['tweet'].apply(removePunc)
df['tweet'] = df['tweet'].apply(removeSymbols)

# Normalize through stemming

def stemming(text):
   stem=[]
   stopword = stopwords.words('english')
   ss = SnowballStemmer('english')
   tokens = nltk.word_tokenize(text)
   text = [ss.stem(word) for word in tokens]
   result=' '.join(text)
   return result
In [21]:
df['tweet'] = df['tweet'].apply(stemming)
In [25]:

In [32]:
# Set labels

def categorise(sentiment, neg_threshold=-0.05, pos_threshold=0.05):
    if sentiment < neg_threshold:
        label = 'negative'
    elif sentiment > pos_threshold:
        label = 'positive'
    else:
        label = 'neutral'
    return label
In [40]:
df['tweetSentiment'] = df['sentiments'].apply(categorise)
df = df[['Candidate','tweet','tweetSentiment']]

from wordcloud import WordCloud, STOPWORDS, ImageColorGenerator

def word_cloud(wd_list):
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS)
    all_words = ' '.join([text for text in wd_list])
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        stopwords=stopwords,
        width=1600,
        height=800,
        random_state=1,
        colormap='jet',
        max_words=80,
        max_font_size=200).generate(all_words)
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 10))
    plt.axis('off')
    plt.imshow(wordcloud, interpolation="bilinear")

Classification¶

Before I go into classification, let's discuss what I am trying to achieve.

The part that I am only interested in whether an user is likely to vote for Trump or Biden. That means their tweet will suggest a postive sentiment toward their candidate. As a result, I only want the tweets with the sentmiments that are positve. After that, I am going to use those tweets to make our predictions. In other words, I only need the tweets that gives me positve sentiment rather than neurtal or negative.

import spacy

nlp = spacy.load(
    "en_core_web_sm",
    exclude=["tagger", "parser", "ner", "lemmatizer", "attribute_ruler"],
)


def tokenize(text):
    doc = nlp.tokenizer(text)
    return [t.norm_ for t in doc if not (t.is_space or t.is_punct or t.like_num)]

Summary & Conclusion¶

  • For this project I used the Sentiment Analysis US Presidential Elections 2020 Dataset from Kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/manchunhui/us-election-2020-tweets

  • During the preprocessing and data cleaning part, I created an extra column on each of the dataframe to identify the whos the tweets are about and drop the columns that I don't need merged the two dataset. In addition, you will see functions that cleans out the numbers, especial characters, numerical values and stopwords.

  • The to set the sentiments for the tweets, NLTKs pre-trained sentiment analyzer, VADER was used to determine the polarity scores. Which was then converted to labels such as positive, negative, and neurtral based on the threshold's value.

  • After assigning the sentiments to the tweets, I wanted to check their distribution. The results show that most of the tweets had positive sentiments toward Biden and a rather more negative toward Trump.

  • During the classification process, I was only interested in whether an user is likely to vote for Trump or Biden. So, I left out all the tweets that are not positve. After that, I used those tweets to make my predictions.

  • Before I could build my classification model, there were some more preprocessing. The data was tokenzied using SpaCy and vectorized using TfidfVectorizer from the SK Learn to transform text to feature vectors that we can use for our model.

  • I split the data into training and testing set with random_state=42 and test size of 30 percant of the total processed data. And then trained my model using a Bernoulli Nave Bayes Classifier

  • Fianlly we make the prediction. The training-set yeilded an accuracy score is 0.871 while the test-set accuracy to be 0.767. These two values shows there is a slight sign of overfitting. Using the mean cross-validation, Ican say that the model is expected to be 76% accurate on an average basis.
